January 1 in Whistler ⛷️

My second time skiing and I really feel like I look cool until I see video footage 🙃😜

In an act of immense nostalgia I read the journal I kept from last season. I came across this entry from the first day of nationals 2022 (swipe to read). 

I found it intriguing that many of my thoughts were centred around enjoying myself. I wish I would’ve tried not to force it so much and allowed myself to be as I was. I remember wanting (needing!) to win so desperately. A year later, I can count on one hand how many times I’ve thought about that particular title. The memories of the performances themselves come much more frequently.
I am looking forward (with cautious optimism) to attending as a spectator this year! 

For all those competing, I wish you personal bests and the strength and grit to accomplish all of your goals. I hope you take a minute to enjoy yourself too! Remember, if you feel like you’re going to be sick and your arms are shaky, don’t worry!! You will absolutely feel better when you get there and you absolutely can do this 🥰

It has officially been 100 days since we have been sleeping on our Endy mattress. You couldn’t PAY ME to give it back!! 
I used to be a terrible sleeper! Stress, compounded with the wrong mattress, compounded with dogs moving around throughout the night. Endy can’t really help with the stress factor (though retiring from Olympic sport pretty much takes care of that one 😜), but for comfort level and uninterrupted REM, they are unparalleled. 
I’ve spoken about the motion minimizing quality in the mattress before but it truly is a game changer if you’re a light sleeper. 
@endy is Canadian, vegan, cruelty free, and they offer a 100 night trial and a 10 year warranty.
Visit the link in my bio to purchase yours!

As young as 7 years old, my only dream was to go to the Olympics. I had hoped to go in 2010, as evidenced by the last photo. As it would turn out, I wasn’t quite ready 😝
Some things I wish I knew, pre-Olympics:

~ The little things are actually the big things. Enjoy them!
~ Pace yourself. It’s a 3.5 week marathon. There is enough time to see and do everything.
~ Nobody really cares what you’re doing or how you’re doing it. Do your best with what you know right now. Similarly, no one is paying attention to what you’re eating in the cafeteria.
~ Write things down. All the things. You will not remember as much as you think.
~ Lean in to the ‘noise.’ It’s not going anywhere.
~ Put your phone down. No one is ever going to watch 800 videos of opening ceremonies. The feeling doesn’t translate anyway.
~ Meet people from other sports! Different athlete perspectives are interesting and you might learn something.
~ You are not too cool for the village arcade.
~ Canada house is the sh*t.
~ Use the resources available to you. Everybody wants to help!
~ Take an extra minute on the ice for reflection. You did the thing!

I recently found the letter pictured in the last photo at my parents’ house. It was in an envelope titled ‘DO NOT OPEN UNTIL 2010’ 🤦🏼‍♀️. I had to blur out a section of it because it is SO cringe 😅. 

Keep dreaming and Happy Olympic Day!

Kirsten Moore-Towers (age 30, turning 31 in July 2023🤣)

Alex 💔
The most perfect friend, daughter, sister, wife and above all, mother to Charlie. She held us all together. I am forever changed for knowing her, and forever changed that she’s gone. 

Please send every ounce of healing and love to Mitch, Charlie, the Paul’s, and the Islam’s as they try to navigate this unfathomable loss 🕊️

Barcelona, Spain, on August 22nd. 
Three weeks ago today, in the most perfect and spontaneous way, we got engaged. 
We would learn four hours later that we lost Alex.
It’s been difficult, to say the least, to feel any kind of joy surrounding our engagement but I know with time we will be able to share in the same excitement we had during these videos 🤍

It’s competition day at Skate Canada International and I am commentating as a part of @skate_canada ‘s broadcast team. I am having the best time! Back in 2018, our national championships were here, in Vancouver where we had our final qualification event for making the Olympic team. This venue is home to my favourite day of my entire career. 
I’m nostalgic and so excited to watch the athletes. Maybe somebody else will have their favourite day of their career so far 😉
